This tree, commonly known as wild almond, bitter almond, or ghoeboontjie, is native to South Africa's Western Cape Province, where it thrives in thickets along stream banks. It stands out botanically as Africa's sole representative of the extensive grevilleoid subfamily. The tree has a bushy appearance with branches spreading widely at ground level and numerous erect stems. Its leaves, up to 6 inches (15 cm) long, are narrow, bluntly toothed, and typically arranged in whorls of six along the branches. During summer, the plant produces white flowers densely packed on spikes emerging from rusty buds at the leaf axils. In autumn, it bears fruits resembling almonds, ranging from magenta to reddish-brown, though too bitter for consumption. In the past, these nuts were boiled, roasted, and ground to make a coffee-like beverage.
